const a = [
  {"id":6540,"text":"Which of the following is the precursor of adenine monophosphate and guanine monophosphate ?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 295.","responses":[{"text":"Phosphoribosyl triphosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orotate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inosine monophosphate (IMP)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutamine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6733,"text":"Penile urethra is mainly formed from which of the following?","explanation":"During embryonic development, the urogenital sinus is divided into three parts: the vesical part, the pelvic part, and the phallic part. The penile (or spongy) urethra, which runs through the length of the penis, originates from the **phallic portion of the urogenital sinus.**","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 267-268.","responses":[{"text":"Surface ectoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vesical part of urogenital sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pelvic part of urogenital sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phallic part of urogenital sinus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":6827,"text":"An increase in which of the following leads to a subsequent decrease in the glomerular filtration rate?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 333.","responses":[{"text":"Peritubular capillary hydrostatic pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glomerular capillary hydrostatic pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glomerular capillary plasma oncotic pressure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bowman's capsule plasma oncotic pressure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13004,"text":"Which of the following is the correct order of the coverings of the kidneys from outwards to inwards?","explanation":"The kidneys are retroperitoneal organs, meaning they are located posterior to the peritoneum. From the outermost layer to the innermost:\r\n\r\n1. **Paranephric fat (or perirenal fat)**: This is the outermost adipose tissue that surrounds the kidneys but is external to the renal fascia.\r\n  \r\n2. **Renal fascia (or Gerota’s fascia)**: A layer of connective tissue that envelops the kidneys and the perinephric fat, providing an anchoring sheath.\r\n\r\n3. **Perinephric fat**: An immediate layer of adipose tissue that directly surrounds the renal capsule and is contained within the renal fascia.\r\n\r\n4. **Renal capsule**: The innermost tough fibrous layer that tightly adheres to the kidney's surface, offering protection from trauma and infection.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 515.","responses":[{"text":"Renal fascia - Perinephric fat - Paranephric fat - Renal capsule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal capsule - Renal fascia - Perinephric fat - Paranephric fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paranephric fat - Renal fascia - Perinephric fat - Renal capsule","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal capsule - Paranephric fat - Perinephric fat - Renal fascia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perinephric fat - Renal fascia - Paranephric fat - Renal capsule","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16013,"text":"A 5-year-old boy presents to the outpatient clinic with generalized edema and periorbital edema. Blood tests and urine analysis reveal hypoalbuminemia, lipiduria, and 3.7 g proteinuria. A renal biopsy is performed. Which of the following electron microscopic features is most likely to be present in this case?","explanation":"The clinical presentation of the boy suggests nephrotic syndrome. Nephrotic syndrome is characterized by heavy proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, edema, and lipiduria. The most common cause of primary nephrotic syndrome in children is Minimal Change Disease (MCD). Electron microscopy in MCD reveals the effacement (flattening) of the foot processes of the podocytes, but immune deposits are typically absent. This feature distinguishes MCD from other forms of nephrotic syndrome. The exact pathogenesis remains unclear, but it is thought that a circulating factor may lead to podocyte injury. While the microscopic appearance of glomeruli on light microscopy is usually normal, electron microscopy provides the defining feature for diagnosis.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 127, 128.","responses":[{"text":"Crescent shaped glomeruli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subepithelial deposits","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subendothelial deposits","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thick glomerular basement membrane with immune complex deposition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Effacement of foot process but no deposits","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22284,"text":"The kidneys are supplied by blood via renal arteries which arise directly from the abdominal aorta immediately distal to the origin of which of the following?","explanation":"The **superior mesenteric artery** is a major branch of the abdominal aorta that supplies blood to a large portion of the intestinal tract. The renal arteries branch off the abdominal aorta just below this artery.\r\n\r\nThe splenic artery and the left gastric artery are branches of the celiac trunk, which is the first major branch of the abdominal aorta.\r\nThe celiac trunk itself arises just below the aortic hiatus of the diaphragm and supplies blood to the stomach, spleen, and liver.\r\nThe inferior mesenteric artery is another major branch of the abdominal aorta but arises significantly lower than the renal arteries, supplying blood to the distal portion of the colon and the rectum","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 379.","responses":[{"text":"Splenic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior mesenteric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Celiac trunk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left gastric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior mesenteric artery","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22285,"text":"During a dissection class, second-year medical students discuss facts about the covering of the kidney. Which of the following statements is true?","explanation":"The **renal fascia,** also known as Gerota's fascia, is a layer of connective tissue that encapsulates the kidney and the **suprarenal (adrenal) gland.** This fascial layer provides support and maintains the position of these organs within the abdominal cavity.\r\n\r\nPerirenal fat, which surrounds the kidney, actually lies internal to the renal fascia. \r\nThe renal fascia does not directly cover the kidney; The direct covering of the kidney is the renal capsule.\r\nPararenal fat, which is the outermost layer surrounding the kidney, does not continue with the fascia iliaca.\r\nPerirenal fat is not continuous with the fascia transversalis. The fascia transversalis lies posterior to the peritoneum and is not directly involved with the kidney's covering.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 377.","responses":[{"text":"Perirenal fat lies external to the renal fascia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal fascia encloses the suprarenal gland","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pararenal fat continues with fascia iliaca","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perirenal fat continues with fascia transversalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal fascia directly covers the kidney","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22286,"text":"The fusion of the lower pole of the kidney, causing the ureters to pass anterior to the isthmus of the kidney, is referred to as which of the following?","explanation":"**Horseshoe kidney** is a congenital anomaly that occurs during embryonic development. Normally, the kidneys ascend from their initial pelvic location to their final position in the upper abdominal region. However, in the case of horseshoe kidney, the lower poles of the kidneys become fused as they ascend. This fusion results in the kidneys adopting a horseshoe-like shape, with the isthmus (a band of tissue) connecting the lower poles across the midline of the body.\r\n\r\nAs a consequence of this fusion, the ureters, which carry urine from the kidneys to the bladder, pass anterior to the isthmus before entering the bladder. Horseshoe kidney is the most common fusion anomaly of the kidneys.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 250.","responses":[{"text":"Rosette kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unilateral double kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aberrant kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pelvic kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Horseshoe kidney","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22287,"text":"The trigone of the urinary bladder develops from which of the following?","explanation":"The trigone of the urinary bladder develops from the **absorbed mesonephric ducts**. During embryological development, the mesonephric ducts, also known as Wolffian ducts, play a crucial role in the formation of certain urinary and genital structures in both males and females. In the development of the urinary bladder, the caudal ends of the mesonephric ducts are absorbed into the posterior wall of the bladder, contributing to the formation of the trigone.\r\n\r\nThe trigone is a smooth triangular area located on the internal surface of the bladder base, between the openings of the ureters and the urethra.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 255.","responses":[{"text":"Phallic part of urogenital sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Absorbed mesonephric duct","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vesical part of urogenital sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pelvic part of urogenital sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paramesonephric duct","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22288,"text":"A 35-year-old male patient comes to the emergency department with a complaint of throbbing pain in the left loin radiating towards the ipsilateral groin. On radiological investigation, a ureteric calculus is seen. The calculus is likely to be lodged at which of the following sites?","explanation":"When a kidney stone (ureteric calculus) becomes lodged within the ureter, it can cause severe pain and discomfort. The specific location of the pain can vary depending on where the stone is situated within the ureter. In this case, the patient's complaint of throbbing pain in the left loin radiating towards the ipsilateral (same-side) groin suggests that the stone is likely obstructing the **uretero-pelvic junction.**\r\n\r\nThe uretero-pelvic junction is the point where the ureter connects to the renal pelvis within the kidney. When a stone blocks this junction, it can impede the flow of urine from the kidney into the ureter, causing pressure buildup and resulting in intense pain.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 381.","responses":[{"text":"Uretero-pelvic junction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trigone of the bladder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal medulla","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pelvic outlet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal papilla","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22289,"text":"The lymphatics from the middle part of the ureter drain into which of the following groups of lymph nodes?","explanation":"The middle part of the ureter corresponds to the area that is situated between the upper and lower thirds of the ureter. This region primarily drains into the **common iliac lymph nodes,** which are located near the common iliac arteries and veins in the pelvic area.","reference":"Moore KL, Dalley AF, Agur AMR. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer/Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins Health; 2014: 296.","responses":[{"text":"Celiac nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common iliac nodes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Para-aortic group","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal iliac nodes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22291,"text":"Which of the following structures plays a key role in the countercurrent multiplication mechanism for concentrating urine in the nephron?","explanation":"The **loop of Henle** consists of two limbs, the descending limb and the ascending limb, and it extends into the renal medulla. The countercurrent multiplication mechanism is a complex and efficient process that involves the interaction between these two limbs.\r\n\r\nAs the filtrate flows through the descending limb, it becomes more concentrated due to the passive reabsorption of water, driven by the hypertonic medullary interstitium. The descending limb is highly permeable to water but not to solutes, allowing water to leave the tubular fluid and enter the surrounding interstitial space.\r\n\r\nIn the ascending limb, the thick ascending limb, in particular, actively transports sodium, potassium, and chloride ions out of the tubular fluid into the interstitium. This active transport sets up an osmotic gradient that drives further water reabsorption in the descending limb, leading to the concentration of urine.\r\n\r\nThe Vasa Recta, a network of blood vessels, also plays a role by maintaining the osmotic gradient within the renal medulla, contributing to the countercurrent multiplication mechanism.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 368.","responses":[{"text":"Proximal convoluted tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Distal convoluted tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loop of Henle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasa Recta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bowman's capsule","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22292,"text":"What type of transport mechanism exemplifies the sodium-potassium-chloride (Na-K-2Cl) transporter located on the apical membrane in the thick ascending limb of the Loop of Henle?","explanation":"**Secondary active transport,** also known as cotransport or symport, is a mechanism that utilizes the energy generated by the primary active transport of one ion (usually sodium) to move another ion or molecule against its concentration gradient. In this case, the transporter uses the energy derived from the active transport of sodium (via the sodium-potassium pump) to facilitate the reabsorption of sodium, potassium, and chloride ions from the tubular lumen into the epithelial cells of the thick ascending limb.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 351.","responses":[{"text":"Passive transport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Counter transport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary active transport","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Facilitated diffusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary active transport","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22293,"text":"A 65-year-old male is admitted to the hospital with symptoms of confusion, hyponatremia, and concentrated urine. The patient's medical history includes lung cancer and recent chemotherapy. Laboratory tests reveal low serum sodium levels and high urine osmolality. What is the most likely cause of the patient's symptoms?","explanation":"**SIADH** is a condition characterized by the excessive release of antidiuretic hormone (ADH) or vasopressin from the posterior pituitary gland, even when serum osmolality is low or normal. ADH acts on the renal collecting ducts, increasing water reabsorption and concentrating urine. This leads to water retention, dilutional hyponatremia (low serum sodium levels), and concentrated urine despite adequate hydration.\r\n\r\nIn the case of this patient, several factors may contribute to SIADH, including lung cancer and recent chemotherapy.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 374.","responses":[{"text":"Syndrome of inappropriate ADH secretion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperaldosteronism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes insipidus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22294,"text":"A 55-year-old female undergoes a renal clearance test to assess the clearance of a substance that is freely filtered at the glomerulus and neither reabsorbed nor secreted by the renal tubules. The clearance value for this substance is found to be equal to the patient's glomerular filtration rate (GFR). Which of the following substances is most likely being measured in this test?","explanation":"**Inulin** is a polysaccharide that is freely filtered at the glomerulus and is neither reabsorbed nor secreted by the renal tubules. It is an ideal substance for estimating the glomerular filtration rate (GFR), which is a key parameter used to assess kidney function. \r\n\r\nWhen the clearance value of a substance matches the GFR, it means that substance is neither reabsorbed nor secreted by the renal tubules and is freely filtered, just like inulin. Therefore, inulin clearance provides an accurate measurement of the GFR, allowing clinicians to evaluate the kidney's ability to filter blood and estimate overall kidney function.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 355.","responses":[{"text":"Creatinine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inulin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22297,"text":"A 55-year-old male is admitted to the hospital with complaints of excessive thirst and polyuria (excessive urine production). Laboratory tests reveal low urine osmolarity. Which of the following is the most likely explanation for the patient's symptoms?","explanation":"ADH plays an important role in regulating water reabsorption in the renal tubules. When ADH is released in response to increased plasma osmolarity or decreased blood volume, it acts on the collecting ducts and distal convoluted tubules, increasing their permeability to water. This allows for the reabsorption of water from the filtrate back into the bloodstream, reducing urine volume and increasing urine osmolarity.\r\n\r\nIn the case of **impaired ADH release,** as seen in conditions like diabetes insipidus, the renal tubules remain impermeable to water, leading to the excretion of large volumes of dilute urine. This results in dehydration and excessive thirst as the body tries to compensate for the fluid loss.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 359.","responses":[{"text":"Reduced secretion of renin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Excessive release of aldosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased reabsorption of Na+ in the proximal tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Impaired release of antidiuretic hormone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inadequate glomerular filtration rate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22299,"text":"Which of the following glucose transporters is primarily responsible for 90% of glucose reabsorption from the brush border epithelium of proximal convoluted tubules?","explanation":"SGLT stands for **Sodium-Glucose Co-Transporter**, and there are two main isoforms: SGLT1 and SGLT2. **SGLT2** is specifically found in the S1 segment of the proximal tubules. This transporter couples the active transport of sodium ions (Na+) with the transport of glucose molecules into the tubular cells from the glomerular filtrate. As sodium is actively reabsorbed, glucose is co-transported along with it, against its concentration gradient.\r\n\r\nThe remaining 10% of glucose reabsorption in the proximal convoluted tubules is mediated by **SGLT1**, which is primarily found in the S3 segment of the proximal tubules.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 345.","responses":[{"text":"SGLT1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"SGLT2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22300,"text":"A research group is studying the functions of specific transporters in the renal tubules to assess their role in maintaining homeostasis. In this context, which of the following functions should be investigated to determine the primary role of pendrin in the renal tubules?","explanation":"Pendrin, encoded by the SLC26A4 gene, is an anion exchanger that is predominantly found in the apical membrane of certain tubular cells in the kidneys, including the type B intercalated cells of the collecting ducts.\r\n\r\nPendrin plays a crucial role in the process of bicarbonate reabsorption and hydrogen ion secretion in the renal tubules. Specifically, it is involved in the secretion of bicarbonate ions (HCO3-) into the tubular lumen and the reabsorption of chloride ions (Cl-) from the tubular lumen. This action is essential for the **regulation of the body's acid-base balance,** helping to excrete excess bicarbonate when the body is in an alkalotic state and retain bicarbonate when it is in an acidotic state.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 353.","responses":[{"text":"Regulating blood pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facilitating glucose reabsorption","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maintaining acid-base balance","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Reabsorbing sodium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enhancing water reabsorption","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22301,"text":"A 42-year-old female is being treated for hypertension and is prescribed a diuretic that inhibits sodium reabsorption in the early distal convoluted tubule. Which type of diuretic is most likely being used?","explanation":"**Thiazide diuretics** are commonly used to treat hypertension by promoting the excretion of sodium and water in the urine, which reduces blood volume and subsequently lowers blood pressure.\r\n\r\nIn the nephron, thiazide diuretics act on the early distal convoluted tubule by inhibiting the sodium-chloride cotransporter (NCC) located in the luminal membrane of tubular cells. By blocking this transporter, thiazides prevent the reabsorption of sodium and chloride ions from the tubular fluid into the tubular cells. As a result, more sodium and chloride remain in the tubular fluid, leading to increased excretion of these ions in the urine. This enhanced excretion of sodium is accompanied by water, reducing overall blood volume and blood pressure.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 422.","responses":[{"text":"Carbonic anhydrase inhibitor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loop diuretic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thiazide diuretic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Osmotic diuretic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aldosterone antagonist","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22302,"text":"Which segment of the renal tubule is water impermeable, allowing solutes like sodium and chloride to passively diffuse into the medullary interstitial space?","explanation":"The segment of the renal tubule that is water impermeable and allows solutes like sodium and chloride to passively diffuse into the medullary interstitial space is the **thin ascending limb of the loop of Henle**. \r\n\r\nIn the thin ascending limb, cells are impermeable to water but passively transport sodium and chloride out of the filtrate into the medullary interstitial space. This process is mediated by the Na+/K+/2Cl- cotransporter in the apical membrane of the tubule cells. The active transport of these ions out of the tubule lumen without accompanying water movement leads to the dilution of the tubular fluid, creating a hypotonic urine relative to the surrounding interstitium.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 369.","responses":[{"text":"Distal convoluted tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proximal convoluted tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thin ascending limb loop of Henle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Descending limb loop of Henle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thick ascending limb loop of Henle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22303,"text":"Which of the following is the most abundant closed buffer in the proximal tubular fluid?","explanation":"**Bicarbonate** is an essential component of the bicarbonate buffer system, which plays a crucial role in maintaining the acid-base balance within the body. This buffer system helps regulate the pH of the urine and prevents excessive acidity or alkalinity.\r\n\r\nAs filtrate flows through the proximal tubules, bicarbonate ions are reabsorbed from the tubular fluid and returned to the bloodstream. This reabsorption process allows the kidneys to conserve bicarbonate.","reference":"Curthoys NP, Moe OW. Proximal tubule function and response to acidosis. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2014;9(9):1627-1638. doi:10.2215/CJN.10391012","responses":[{"text":"Bicarbonate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lactate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ammonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proteins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22304,"text":"A patient is undergoing a renal function test to determine the clearance of substance X. After a urine collection period, it is found that the concentration of substance X in urine (U) is 200 mg/dL, the concentration of substance X in plasma (P) is 20 mg/dL, and the urine flow rate (V) is 1.2 mL/min. What would be the renal clearance of substance X?","explanation":"The renal clearance of a substance can be calculated using the formula:\r\n\r\nC = UV/P\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n**C** represents the renal clearance of the substance.\r\n**U** is the concentration of the substance in urine.\r\n**V** is the urine flow rate.\r\n**P** is the concentration of the substance in plasma.\r\n\r\nIn this case, we have the following values:\r\n**U (concentration of substance X in urine)** = 200 mg/dL\r\n**V (urine flow rate)** = 1.2 mL/min\r\n**P (concentration of substance X in plasma)** = 20 mg/dL\r\n\r\nNow, we can calculate the renal clearance (C) of substance X:\r\n\r\nC = 200 mg/dl x 1.2 ml/min / 20 mg/dl = 240/12 = 12 ml/min\r\n\r\nSo, the renal clearance of substance X is **12 mL/min**.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 361.","responses":[{"text":"C= 12 mL/min","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"C= 2 mL/min","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C= 0.1 mL/min","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C= 1200 mL/min","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C= 200 mL/min","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22305,"text":"Two samples of filtrate are taken from the beginning and end of the proximal tubules by a micropipette for comparison. Which one of the following substances would be present in large quantity at the end as compared to the beginning?","explanation":"In the proximal tubules, a significant portion of substances such as glucose, amino acids, and sodium are reabsorbed back into the bloodstream. However, **chloride** ion reabsorption in the proximal tubule happens somewhat differently.\r\n\r\nInitially, chloride concentration is lower in the filtrate compared to the plasma due to the active reabsorption of other ions and substances like sodium, glucose, and amino acids. This active reabsorption creates an osmotic and electrical gradient that drives the passive reabsorption of chloride later in the proximal tubule. Consequently, the chloride concentration initially remains relatively unchanged or even decreases slightly at the beginning of the proximal tubule, but then it increases as water is reabsorbed and chloride is left behind. By the end of the proximal tubule, the chloride concentration is higher relative to the filtrate's volume, hence more concentrated.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 349.","responses":[{"text":"Amino acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloride","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22306,"text":"In an experiment, 5 grams of substance A is found to be filtered at the glomeruli per day, while 7 grams of the same substance is excreted in urine per day. Which one of the following statements justifies the above condition?","explanation":"In the described experiment, where 5 grams of substance A is filtered at the glomeruli per day but 7 grams of the same substance is excreted in the urine per day, the most appropriate explanation is that the **Substance is secreted by the nephron**. This conclusion is drawn from the fact that the amount of substance excreted in the urine is greater than the amount filtered by the glomeruli.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 329.","responses":[{"text":"All of that substance is reabsorbed","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Substance is both reabsorbed and secreted","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rate of filtration equals rate of excretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Substance is synthesized in the tubular cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Substance is secreted by the nephron","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22320,"text":"Which blood vessels surround the loops of Henle?","explanation":"The **vasa recta** are specialized capillaries that play a crucial role in maintaining the osmotic gradient in the renal medulla, which is essential for the kidney's ability to concentrate urine. These capillaries closely follow the loops of Henle, both the descending and ascending limbs, and are arranged in a hairpin-like fashion. \r\n\r\nThe vasa recta are responsible for reabsorbing water and solutes from the interstitial fluid of the medulla, which helps prevent the washout of concentrated solutes created by the nephron's countercurrent mechanism. This arrangement allows the kidney to concentrate urine effectively, conserving water and maintaining the body's fluid balance.","reference":"Vasa recta - an overview | ScienceDirect Topics. Accessed January 3, 2024. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/veterinary-science-and-veterinary-medicine/vasa-recta","responses":[{"text":"Efferent arterioles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interlobular arteries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peritubular capillaries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasa recta","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Interlobar arteries","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22338,"text":"Cytidine triphosphate (CTP) is produced by the amination of UTP (Uridine triphosphate) by which one of the following enzymes?","explanation":"Cytidine triphosphate (CTP) is produced from Uridine triphosphate (UTP) through a process called amination, and the enzyme responsible for this conversion is **CTP synthetase**. CTP synthetase catalyzes the addition of an amine group (NH₃) to UTP, converting it into CTP, which is an essential nucleotide for the synthesis of RNA and the regulation of lipid metabolism.\r\n\r\nThis reaction is part of the pyrimidine nucleotide biosynthesis pathway. CTP synthetase activity is a key regulatory point in the synthesis of pyrimidine nucleotides, ensuring the balance and availability of CTP for various biochemical processes within the cell.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 303.","responses":[{"text":"UTP transferase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CTP synthetase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ribonucleotide reductase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CTP synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CTP kinase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22339,"text":"A 3-month-old infant was brought to the outpatient department with a complaint of an eczematous rash along with vomiting. In addition, he had a musty and mousy odor in his urine. The infant had blond hair, blue eyes along with fair skin. Which of the following diseases is most likely to be linked in this case?","explanation":"**Phenylketonuria (PKU)** is an autosomal recessive metabolic disorder characterized by a deficiency of the enzyme phenylalanine hydroxylase, which is responsible for converting the amino acid phenylalanine to tyrosine. In individuals with PKU, phenylalanine accumulates in the body, leading to various clinical manifestations.\r\n\r\nThe eczematous rash, vomiting, and the musty or mousy odor in the urine are classic signs of PKU. The skin findings and the odor are due to the accumulation of phenylalanine and its breakdown products in the body. Additionally, PKU can lead to intellectual disability and developmental delay if not managed properly.\r\n\r\nThe fair complexion, blond hair, and blue eyes of the infant are characteristic of individuals with PKU. Early diagnosis and strict dietary management, which restricts phenylalanine intake, are essential to prevent the neurological and developmental complications associated with this condition.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 271.","responses":[{"text":"Phenylketonuria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystinuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetic ketoacidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maple syrup disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycinuria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22340,"text":"Many substances are cleared by the kidney. Under normal physiological conditions the clearance of which of the following substances is zero?","explanation":"**Glucose** is typically completely reabsorbed by the renal tubules in a healthy individual. The reabsorption of glucose occurs primarily in the proximal convoluted tubules, where glucose is actively transported back into the bloodstream. The renal threshold for glucose reabsorption is around 180-200 mg/dL of plasma glucose. \r\n\r\nWhen blood glucose levels are within the normal range (usually below this threshold), all the filtered glucose is effectively reabsorbed, and there is no glucose present in the urine. This efficient reabsorption prevents the loss of glucose in the urine and helps to maintain normal blood glucose levels.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 345.","responses":[{"text":"Inulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Creatinine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Phenolphthalein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PAH","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22342,"text":"Which one of the following actions is inhibited by parathyroid hormone in the renal tubules?","explanation":"When blood calcium levels are low, the parathyroid glands release PTH, which has several effects on the kidneys. One of its main actions is to reduce the **reabsorption of phosphate in the proximal tubules.** This leads to an increase in the excretion of phosphate in the urine. By doing so, PTH helps to raise blood calcium levels indirectly because phosphate and calcium have an inverse relationship in their renal handling.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 358.","responses":[{"text":"Phosphate secretion in proximal tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium reabsorption in distal tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphate reabsorption in proximal tubule","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium secretion in distal tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium reabsorption in loop of Henle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22343,"text":"A healthy 25-year-old male participates in a marathon race on a hot and humid day and becomes dehydrated. In which of the following segments of his nephron, maximum water will be reabsorbed in the presence of high levels of antidiuretic hormone (ADH)?","explanation":"During dehydration, the body's primary goal is to conserve water. In response to this state, the hypothalamus signals the release of ADH from the posterior pituitary gland. ADH acts on the **collecting ducts** of the nephron to increase their permeability to water. \r\n\r\nThe collecting ducts are the final segment of the nephron where water reabsorption takes place before urine is excreted. When ADH is present, it inserts aquaporin water channels into the collecting duct cells' luminal membrane, allowing for the passive reabsorption of water. As a result, more water is reabsorbed from the urine, concentrating it and conserving body fluids in conditions of dehydration. This physiological response helps to maintain overall body water balance during challenging situations like a marathon on a hot and humid day.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 348.","responses":[{"text":"Descending limb of Loop of Henle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Distal convoluted tubules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proximal convoluted tubules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collecting tubules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collecting ducts","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22344,"text":"The arterial blood gas (ABG) analysis of a 44-year-old female with a history of severe diarrhea showed a pH of 7.25, PCO2= 24 mmHg, HCO3= 10mEq/L, and K+= 2.5mEq/l. Which one of the following conditions is the most appropriate diagnosis?","explanation":"The combination of ABG values indicates a **metabolic acidosis.** The low pH suggests acidemia, and the low bicarbonate (HCO3) level, along with normal PCO2, points towards a primary metabolic acidosis. The reduced bicarbonate level suggests that the body is unable to effectively buffer excess acids or has lost bicarbonate, which is consistent with metabolic acidosis. Additionally, the low potassium (K+) level may be related to metabolic acidosis.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 417.","responses":[{"text":"Metabolic alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal status","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic acidosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22345,"text":"What is the net filtration pressure at the glomerulus if the glomerular hydrostatic pressure is 44 mmHg, Bowman's capsule hydrostatic pressure is 9mmHg, the osmotic pressure of plasma is 28mmHg, and the osmotic pressure of the tubular fluid is 0mmHg?","explanation":"The net filtration pressure (NFP) at the glomerulus is calculated as the difference between the glomerular hydrostatic pressure (PG), Bowman's capsule hydrostatic pressure (PB), and the colloid osmotic pressure of plasma (πG), minus the colloid osmotic pressure of the tubular fluid (πB). \r\n\r\nGiven the values:\r\n- Glomerular hydrostatic pressure (PG) = 44 mmHg\r\n- Bowman's capsule hydrostatic pressure (PB) = 9 mmHg\r\n- Osmotic pressure of plasma (πG) = 28 mmHg\r\n- Osmotic pressure of tubular fluid (πB) = 0 mmHg\r\n\r\nWe can calculate the NFP as follows:\r\nNFP = (PG - PB) - (πG - πB)\r\nNFP = (44 mmHg - 9 mmHg) - (28 mmHg - 0 mmHg)\r\nNFP = 35 mmHg - 28 mmHg\r\nNFP = **7 mmHg**","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 333.","responses":[{"text":"14 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"11 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"7 mmHg","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"18 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"21 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22346,"text":"A 35-year-old female with uncontrolled diabetes was found to have a plasma glucose level of 300 mg/dl with a normal glomerular filtration rate. Which one of the following values corresponds to the calculated filtered load of glucose in this case?","explanation":"Under normal circumstances, the filtered load of glucose is about 125 mg/min, as the GFR is approximately 125 ml/min and the normal plasma glucose concentration is about 1 mg/ml. However, in this patient with a plasma glucose level of 300 mg/dl (or 3 mg/ml), the filtered load significantly increases. The calculation would be as follows:\r\n\r\n- GFR = 125 ml/min\r\n- Plasma Glucose Concentration = 300 mg/dl (which is equivalent to 3 mg/ml)\r\n\r\nTherefore, the filtered load of glucose = GFR × Plasma Glucose Concentration = 125 ml/min × 3 mg/ml = 375 mg/min.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 346.","responses":[{"text":"250 mg/dl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"575 mg/dl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"450 mg/dl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"150 mg/dl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"375 mg/dl","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22351,"text":"In muscle tissue, creatine and phosphocreatine produce creatinine as a waste product excreted from the body. The creatinine clearance test is that it is the marker of which of the following?","explanation":"Creatinine is a waste product generated from the breakdown of creatine and phosphocreatine in muscle tissue. It is constantly produced and released into the bloodstream at a relatively stable rate. However, the kidneys play a pivotal role in removing creatinine from the blood and excreting it in the urine. The rate at which the kidneys clear creatinine from the blood is directly related to their glomerular filtration rate (GFR), which is a measure of how effectively the **glomeruli** (tiny filtering units in the kidneys) **function** in filtering waste products and excess substances from the blood.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 361.","responses":[{"text":"Tubular function","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glomerular function","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Urolithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measurement of skeletal muscle mass","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bladder function","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22352,"text":"In tissues that do not carry out active de novo synthesis, how is an adequate supply of adenine nucleotides maintained?","explanation":"**A-PRT (adenine phosphoribosyltransferase)** is an enzyme that catalyzes the conversion of adenine into adenosine monophosphate (AMP) by transferring a ribose-5-phosphate group from phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate (PRPP). This salvage pathway allows the cell to recycle adenine from degraded nucleotides and use it to regenerate AMP, an essential component of adenine nucleotides like ATP.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 296.","responses":[{"text":"It requires ATP uptake from the blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is accomplished entirely by the action of adenylate kinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It depends upon the action of nucleoside phosphorylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It involves hypoxanthine salvage using HG-PRT","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It occurs primarily by adenine salvage using A-PRT","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22359,"text":"A 55-year-old man presents with hypertension, puffiness of his face, and darkening of urine. Serum levels of blood urea nitrogen (BUN) are raised. Urinalysis reports numerous RBCs and occasional red cell casts. He was admitted for further investigations. Which of the following serum proteins will be found depleted in this patient suggesting an immune-complex mediated renal involvement?","explanation":"The clinical picture in this patient is suggestive of an immune-complex mediated renal involvement, particularly **nephritic syndrome**. \r\n\r\nOne of the key features of nephritic syndrome is the presence of immune complexes in the glomeruli. These immune complexes can activate the complement system. Among the serum proteins involved in the complement system, **Complement C3** is often found to be depleted in cases of immune-complex mediated renal diseases like post-infectious glomerulonephritis.\r\n\r\nThe activation of the complement cascade and subsequent consumption of complement components like C3 are part of the immune response within the glomeruli and contribute to the inflammation and tissue damage observed in nephritic syndrome.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 909.","responses":[{"text":"Complement C3","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hageman factor (factor XII)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amyloid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22360,"text":"A 10-year-old boy abruptly develops malaise, fever, nausea, oliguria, and hematuria (smoky or cola-colored urine) one to two weeks after recovery from a sore throat. The patient has red cell casts in the urine, mild proteinuria (\u003c 1 gm/day), periorbital edema, and mild to moderate hypertension. Which of the following best describes this patient's medical condition?","explanation":"The key clinical features that point towards **nephritic syndrome** include the abrupt onset of symptoms following a recent sore throat, accompanied by malaise, fever, nausea, oliguria, and hematuria (smoky or cola-colored urine). The presence of **red cell casts** in the urine indicates glomerular involvement. Additionally, there is mild proteinuria (\u003c1 gm/day), periorbital edema, and mild to moderate hypertension. \r\n\r\nPost-infectious glomerulonephritis is typically caused by a prior streptococcal infection, often pharyngitis (sore throat) or impetigo. It is characterized by an inflammatory response within the glomeruli due to immune complex deposition. This condition is a classic example of nephritic syndrome, which is characterized by hematuria, proteinuria, hypertension, and renal dysfunction, often triggered by an immune response following an infection.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 130.","responses":[{"text":"Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephritic syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Polycystic kidneys","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranous glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22361,"text":"A 7-year-old boy has been diagnosed with post-infectious glomerulonephritis resulting in nephritic syndrome. The child has hematuria as a part of this syndrome. Which of the following findings on urinalysis would suggest that RBCs in his urine are coming from the kidneys and not from lower down the urinary tract?","explanation":"**Red cell casts** are a distinctive finding that indicates the presence of both red blood cells (RBCs) and casts within the renal tubules. These casts form when RBCs are entrapped in the renal tubules during their passage through the glomerular filtration membrane. The presence of red cell casts is a hallmark of glomerulonephritis, specifically the nephritic syndrome. It indicates that the bleeding or hematuria is of renal origin and originates within the glomeruli or renal tubules.","reference":"Urinary cast - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed January 3, 2024. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/urinary-cast","responses":[{"text":"White cell casts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red cell casts","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Urobilinogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood clots","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophages containing red cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22365,"text":"Muscle-invasive bladder cancers are associated with which of the following?","explanation":"Muscle-invasive bladder cancers are commonly associated with the **inactivation of TP53 \u0026 RB tumor suppressor genes**. \r\n\r\nThe TP53 gene, often referred to as the \"guardian of the genome,\" is crucial for regulating the cell cycle and preventing genomic instability. Its inactivation can lead to uncontrolled cell proliferation and tumor development. Similarly, the RB (retinoblastoma) gene is another key regulator of the cell cycle. Its inactivation can result in unchecked cellular division, contributing to tumorigenesis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 958.","responses":[{"text":"Amplification of c-myc gene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inactivation of TP53 \u0026 Rb tumor suppressor genes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Activations of TP53 \u0026 RB tumor suppressor genes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Translocation of TFE3 gene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gene notations of MET proto-oncogene","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22366,"text":"A 42-year-old man has had recurrent episodes of urinary tract infections (UTIs) over the last six months. Urine culture has yielded the growth of Proteus mirabilis on three occasions. Which one of the following could be the most likely underlying cause?","explanation":"*Proteus mirabilis* is a bacterium known for its association with UTIs, especially in the presence of certain conditions. This bacterium is urease-positive, meaning it can hydrolyze urea to ammonia and carbon dioxide, leading to the development of alkaline urine. Alkaline urine provides an environment conducive to the formation of **struvite stones** (magnesium ammonium phosphate stones) and calcium phosphate stones. These stones can obstruct the urinary tract, create stagnant urine pools, and serve as a nidus for bacterial growth, including Proteus mirabilis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 947.","responses":[{"text":"Reflux nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterovesical fistula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Schistosomiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal calculi","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22367,"text":"A patient with severe recurrent gout, who had been taking high doses of analgesics, presented with malaise and nausea. Laboratory findings showed raised serum urea and creatinine levels. Which one of the following diseases is he suffering from?","explanation":"**Renal papillary necrosis** is a condition characterized by the death of the renal papillae, which are the pointed structures at the tips of the renal pyramids in the kidneys. This condition is often associated with long-term use of high doses of analgesics, especially non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), which are commonly used to manage gout.\r\n\r\nIn this condition, ischemic injury to the renal papillae occurs due to reduced blood flow, leading to necrosis. This can result in symptoms such as malaise, nausea, and elevated serum urea and creatinine levels, as the kidneys' function becomes impaired.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 932.","responses":[{"text":"Renal papillary necrosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydronephrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute tubular injury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephrolithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22368,"text":"A 45-year-old man had left flank pain. Ultrasonography showed bilaterally enlarged kidneys with multiple variable-size cysts in both the cortex and medulla. A few cysts in the liver were also seen. What is the most likely pattern of inheritance of this disease?","explanation":"This condition is consistent with **Autosomal Dominant Polycystic Kidney Disease (ADPKD)**, a genetic disorder where a single mutated copy of the disease-causing gene is sufficient to manifest the disease. ADPKD is usually caused by mutations in the PKD1 or PKD2 genes. Affected individuals have a 50% chance of passing the mutated gene to their offspring, resulting in the autosomal dominant pattern of inheritance.\r\n\r\nTypically, ADPKD presents with progressive kidney enlargement and the development of multiple cysts, leading to renal impairment over time. It can also involve other organs like the liver.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 941-942.","responses":[{"text":"Autosomal recessive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-linked","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal dominant","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytogenetic disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal co-dominant","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22369,"text":"An elderly patient with a history of heart disease has difficulty breathing and is diagnosed with acute pulmonary edema. Which of the following drugs is indicated as a drug of first choice to treat this problem?","explanation":"**Furosemide,** a loop diuretic, acts on the thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle in the nephron, where it inhibits the reabsorption of sodium and chloride ions. This diuretic effect leads to a rapid reduction in blood volume and decreases preload on the heart. In the case of acute pulmonary edema, this is particularly beneficial because it helps to alleviate the congestion in the pulmonary circulation, reducing the excessive accumulation of fluid in the lungs.\r\n\r\nThe rapid onset of action of furosemide makes it a valuable choice in emergencies such as acute pulmonary edema, where prompt relief is essential. It is administered intravenously to achieve a rapid response.","reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 247.","responses":[{"text":"Mannitol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spironolactone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlorthalidone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetazolamide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Furosemide","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22371,"text":"A patient was referred to your clinic by a physician with a note that the patient's chronic illness is not improving despite getting all treatment options for his illness. Evaluate the patient and share your expert opinion. What steps would you like to consider in this case?","explanation":"In managing a patient referred due to non-improvement in their chronic illness despite treatment, a comprehensive approach is necessary. **Evaluating the risk factors and barriers of treatment adherence** is the first step. This involves understanding the patient's lifestyle, socioeconomic status, psychological factors, and any other issues that might hinder adherence to treatment. It is essential to assess whether the patient fully understands the treatment regimen, including the purpose and importance of each medication, and any challenges they might face in following it.\r\n\r\nOnce potential barriers are identified, the next steps are:\r\n\r\n**Ensure compliance of the patient**: This involves checking if the patient is correctly following the prescribed treatment regimen. Non-compliance can often be a major reason for treatment failure. This can be done through direct questioning, pill counts, or monitoring therapeutic levels of medications if applicable.\r\n\r\n**Address the issues of the patient**: It's crucial to have an open and empathetic conversation with the patient to understand their concerns, fears, and misconceptions about the treatment. This step may uncover psychological barriers, misinformation, or misunderstandings about the disease or treatment.\r\n\r\n**Change in medicine/drug regime**: If adherence issues are ruled out, and the patient is still not showing improvement, it may be necessary to re-evaluate the treatment regimen. This could involve adjusting dosages or switching to different medications, considering potential side effects and interactions.\r\n\r\n**Guide the caregiver for adherence**: In cases where the patient relies on a caregiver, educating and engaging the caregiver is crucial. They should be informed about the treatment plan, the importance of adherence, and how they can support the patient.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Renal module, Subject: Behavioral sciences; Topic: Treatment Adherence in Chronic Disease; Sub-topic: Adherence.","responses":[{"text":"Ensure compliance of patient","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Evaluate the risk factors and barriers of treatment adherence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Guide the caregiver for adherence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Address the issues of patient","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Change in medicine/drug regime","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22378,"text":"A 34-year-old female presented to the outpatient department with decreased urination and pedal edema. On examination, there was a renal bruit on the right side. Her blood pressure was 160/100 mmHg. Her primary care physician prescribed her antihypertensive medication a week ago. Her investigations revealed a Hb of 12.1 gm/dl, urea 109 mg/dl, creatinine 4.2 mg/dl, Na⁺ 138 mEq/l, K⁺ 5.4 mEq/L. Which of the following antihypertensive must have been prescribed to her which resulted in increased serum creatinine level?","explanation":"**ACE inhibitors,** such as drugs like enalapril or lisinopril, are known for their antihypertensive properties and are commonly prescribed to manage hypertension. However, one of the side effects associated with ACE inhibitors is **elevated serum creatinine levels**. This occurs due to the dilation of efferent arterioles in the glomerulus, which reduces intraglomerular pressure. While this effect is usually beneficial in controlling blood pressure, it can lead to a **reduction in the glomerular filtration rate (GFR)** and a subsequent increase in serum creatinine.\r\n\r\nIn patients with compromised renal function or renal artery stenosis, ACE inhibitors can further impair kidney function, as they rely on a well-functioning renal system to maintain GFR. In this patient's case, the presence of a renal bruit and elevated serum creatinine levels suggests that the ACE inhibitor may have exacerbated her renal dysfunction, leading to decreased urination and pedal edema.","reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 260.","responses":[{"text":"Beta blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thiazide diuretics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium channel blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ACE inhibitors","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22379,"text":"A 26-year-old female presented to the outpatient department with loose watery stools for 2 days, occurring almost 10-15 episodes per day. It was not associated with fever or blood in stools. On examination, she was severely dehydrated and had decreased urinary output. Her investigations showed a Hb of 15.9 gm/dl, MCV 92, platelets 162 × 10⁹, urea 112 mg/dl, creatinine 4.2 mg/dl, Na⁺ 136 mEq/l, K⁺ 4.2 mEq/L, HCO₃⁻: 16 mEq/L. What should be the immediate treatment?","explanation":"This patient's clinical presentation is indicative of severe dehydration resulting from significant fluid loss due to watery diarrhea. Her laboratory findings, including elevated blood urea and creatinine levels and a low bicarbonate level, suggest acute kidney injury and metabolic acidosis, which can occur as a consequence of severe dehydration.\r\n\r\nTreatment should focus on rapid rehydration to restore adequate blood volume and improve renal perfusion. **Administering intravenous fluids** is essential in this scenario to replace the lost fluids and correct the electrolyte imbalance. Once hydration is improved, further evaluation and management can be considered.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Renal module, Subject: Medicine; Topic: Dehydration/ Overhydration; Sub-topic: Rate of Fluid.","responses":[{"text":"Adequate hydration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral-rehydration salt (ORS)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibiotics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bicarbonate replacement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemodialysis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22380,"text":"A 68-year-old male presented with decreased urinary output and pedal edema for 6 months. He has been diabetic for 30 years and has recently started developing recurrent hypoglycemia. Which of the following tests is most pertinent for establishing chronic kidney disease?","explanation":"Chronic kidney disease is a condition characterized by the gradual loss of kidney function over time.\r\nThe **eGFR** is a calculated estimate of the glomerular filtration rate, which reflects the rate at which the kidneys are filtering waste products and excess substances from the blood. It is considered one of the most reliable indicators of kidney function. In this patient, who presents with decreased urinary output, pedal edema, and a history of diabetes, assessing kidney function is essential as diabetes is a common cause of CKD.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Renal Module, Subject: Medicine; Topic: Chronic Kidney Disease; Sub-topic: Stages of CKD.","responses":[{"text":"Urine DR for proteinuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"eGFR","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Electrolytes and arterial blood gases (ABGs)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urea and creatinine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22381,"text":"A 30-year-old male presents in the emergency department with upper abdominal pain for the last 2 days and gradual deterioration in consciousness over the last 6 hours. He has been previously well. On examination, his blood pressure in 100/70mmHg, pulse 130/minute, respiratory rate 30/min with rapid and deep breathing, and he was afebrile. Arterial blood gas shows pH 7.10, PCO₂ 20 mmHg, PO₂ 60 mmHg, HCO₃ 6 meq/L. What is the acid-base disorder in this scenario?","explanation":"The acid-base disorder presented in this 30-year-old male, based on the arterial blood gas (ABG) values, is **Metabolic acidosis**. The key indicators for this diagnosis are the significantly low pH (7.10) and the markedly reduced bicarbonate level (HCO₃⁻) of 6 meq/L, which is well below the normal range of 22-26 meq/L. \r\n\r\nMetabolic acidosis is characterized by a primary reduction in bicarbonate concentration, leading to a decrease in blood pH. The low PCO₂ of 20 mmHg indicates a compensatory respiratory response, where the body attempts to raise the pH by increasing the respiratory rate (hyperventilation) to blow off CO₂, as CO₂ is an acidic component. This compensatory mechanism is reflected in the patient's rapid and deep breathing.\r\n\r\nThe presentation of upper abdominal pain and rapid deterioration of consciousness in this patient suggests a possible underlying acute medical condition that could be causing the metabolic acidosis, such as diabetic ketoacidosis, lactic acidosis, renal failure, or toxin ingestion.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Renal module, Subject: Medicine; Topic: ABGs and Interpretation; Sub-topic: Characteristics of the Primary Acid-Base Disorders.","responses":[{"text":"Respiratory alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic acidosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"No acid-base disturbance","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22382,"text":"A 30-year-old male presents in the emergency department with sudden loss of consciousness after ingesting some unknown compound. He had been previously well. On examination, his blood pressure is 100/70mmHg, pulse 90/minute, respiratory rate 6/min, and he is afebrile. He is not following commands and does not open his eyes to pain even. Arterial blood gas shows a pH of 7.10, PCO₂ 80 mmHg, PO₂ 60 mmHg, HCO₃, 27 mEq/L. What is the acid-base disorder in this scenario?","explanation":"The acid-base disorder presented in this 30-year-old male patient, as indicated by the arterial blood gas (ABG) values, is **Respiratory acidosis**. This diagnosis is based on the ABG results showing a low pH (7.10), indicating acidemia, and an elevated PCO₂ (80 mmHg), which is indicative of hypoventilation. The normal range for arterial PCO₂ is approximately 35-45 mmHg, and values above this range suggest an accumulation of carbon dioxide in the blood due to inadequate ventilation.\r\n\r\nRespiratory acidosis occurs when there is an accumulation of CO₂ in the bloodstream, typically due to inadequate respiratory function. In this patient, the respiratory rate of 6/min is significantly below the normal range (12-20 breaths per minute), suggesting hypoventilation. This could be due to respiratory depression, possibly caused by the ingestion of a central nervous system depressant or another unknown compound.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Renal module, Subject: Medicine; Topic: ABGs and Interpretation; Sub-topic: Characteristics of the Primary Acid-Base Disorders.","responses":[{"text":"Respiratory acidosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic acidosis with increase anion-gap","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22383,"text":"A 50-year-old male patient has presented with sudden-onset, severe watery diarrhea that has persisted for four days. He experiences approximately 15 episodes of diarrhea per day and also vomiting. There is no blood in the stool. Upon examination, he has marked dehydration, a temperature of 38.5 °C, and a rapid heart rate. Which of the following electrolyte imbalances is he at risk of developing?","explanation":"**Hyponatremia** refers to a lower-than-normal concentration of sodium ions in the blood. In this case, the continuous watery diarrhea and vomiting result in significant fluid loss from the body. Sodium ions are primarily found in extracellular fluid, and when excessive fluid is lost, it can lead to a relative increase in the concentration of sodium in the remaining extracellular fluid, which is detected by the body's osmoreceptors.\r\n\r\nTo correct this imbalance, the body responds by increasing the secretion of antidiuretic hormone (ADH) to retain water and reduce urine output. This ultimately leads to dilutional hyponatremia, where the sodium concentration in the blood becomes lower than normal.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 314.","responses":[{"text":"Hypocalcemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyponatremia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypernatremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypokalemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperkalemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22384,"text":"A 54-year-old male presented to the outpatient department with a history of recurrent headaches due to sinusitis, for which he took non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) regularly. His initial investigations showed a Hb of 11.2 gm/dl, a total leukocyte count (TLC) of 4.8 ×10 ³, 58% neutrophils, 28% lymphocytes, 12% eosinophils, and 2% monocytes. Urea is 98 mg/dl and creatinine is 2.1 gm/dl. Urine analysis is positive for protein. What is the most likely reason for his deranged laboratory tests?","explanation":"**Acute interstitial nephritis** is a common cause of acute kidney injury and is often drug-induced, particularly by NSAIDs. This condition is characterized by inflammation and edema in the interstitium of the kidneys, which can lead to decreased renal function.\r\n\r\nThe patient's symptoms and laboratory findings are consistent with this diagnosis. The elevated urea and creatinine levels indicate impaired renal function. Proteinuria (protein in urine) can occur in interstitial nephritis, although it is usually less severe than in nephrotic syndrome. The presence of eosinophilia (12% eosinophils) in the blood can be an additional clue, as eosinophilia is often associated with drug-induced interstitial nephritis.\r\n\r\nEnd-stage renal disease is a chronic condition with more severe signs and symptoms.\r\nNephrotic syndrome typically presents with heavy proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, and edema.\r\nAcute tubular necrosis, usually caused by ischemia or toxins, often leads to acute kidney injury with features like muddy brown casts in urine, which is not mentioned here.\r\nNephritic syndrome is characterized by hematuria, hypertension, and oliguria, none of which are described in this case.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 932.","responses":[{"text":"Interstitial nephritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephritic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"End-stage renal disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute tubular necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

